  26: * Provides a context of work for database interactions.
  27: * <p>
  28: * A <em>Session</em> is a logical container for a causally chained series of
  29: * {@linkplain Transaction transactions}. Client applications typically work
  30: * with <em>managed transactions</em>, which come in two flavours: transaction
  31: * functions and auto-commit transactions. Managed transactions automatically
  32: * handle the transaction boundaries (<code>BEGIN</code> and
  33: * <code>COMMIT</code>/<code>ROLLBACK</code>) and can also provide other
  34: * supporting features; transaction functions offer retry capabilities, for
  35: * example.
  36: * <p>
  37: * Unmanaged transactions are also available but tend to be used by libraries
  38: * or tooling that require more fine-grained control.
  39: * <p>
  40: * Typically, a session will acquire a TCP connection from a connection pool
  41: * in order to carry out a transaction. Once the transaction has completed,
  42: * and the entire result has been consumed, this connection will be released
  43: * back into the pool. One connection can therefore be adopted by several
  44: * sessions over its lifetime, although it will only be owned by one at a
  45: * time. Client applications should never need to deal directly with
  46: * connection management.
  47: * <p>
  48: * Session implementations are not generally thread-safe. Therefore, multiple
  49: * sessions should be used when an application requires multiple concurrent
  50: * threads of database work to be carried out.
  51: *
  52: * @since 1.0 (Removed async API to {@link AsyncSession} in 4.0)
  53: */
